<subSubSection id="6D837C851034FFABDBE2FE90488729AB" pageId="17" pageNumber="118" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="25262F0E1034FFABDBE2FE90488729AB" blockId="17.[151,1437,150,646]" pageId="17" pageNumber="118">
<emphasis id="17EDF31C1034FFABDBE2FE904D012AD8" bold="true" box="[199,308,475,501]" pageId="17" pageNumber="118">Remarks</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName id="E299548D1034FFABDA60FE904DF62AD8" authorityName="Okajima &amp; Masumoto" authorityYear="2022" box="[325,451,475,501]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Asianthrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="118" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dentipes">
<emphasis id="17EDF31C1034FFABDA60FE904DF62AD8" box="[325,451,475,501]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="118">A. dentipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is presumably related to 
<taxonomicName id="E299548D1034FFABD9CEFE904F4B2AD8" authorityName="Okajima &amp; Masumoto" authorityYear="2022" box="[747,894,475,501]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Asianthrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="118" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dasycornis">
<emphasis id="17EDF31C1034FFABD9CEFE904F4B2AD8" box="[747,894,475,501]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="118">A dasycornis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="E299548D1034FFABD89CFE9048182AD8" authorityName="Okajima &amp; Masumoto" authorityYear="2022" box="[953,1069,475,501]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Asianthrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="118" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="longior">
<emphasis id="17EDF31C1034FFABD89CFE9048182AD8" box="[953,1069,475,501]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="118">A. longior</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by having a series of short and stout setae on the ventral surface of intermediate antennal segments at least in the macropterous female. However, 
<taxonomicName id="E299548D1034FFABDBB2FD684D232910" authorityName="Okajima &amp; Masumoto" authorityYear="2022" box="[151,278,547,573]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Asianthrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="118" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dentipes">
<emphasis id="17EDF31C1034FFABDBB2FD684D232910" box="[151,278,547,573]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="118">A. dentipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is unique in having stout fore tarsal tooth in male (
<figureCitation id="BDA2338B1034FFABD849FD684FF62913" box="[876,963,547,574]" captionStart="FIGURES 62–71" captionStartId="16.[151,264,1896,1920]" captionTargetBox="[178,1410,181,1873]" captionTargetId="figure-29@16.[178,1410,181,1873]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURES 62–71. Asianthrips dentipes, sp. n. (62) Head–pelta (female, mac); (63) Head– pelta (female, mic); (64) Antenna, dorsal aspect (female, mic); (65) Antennal segments III–VIII, ventral aspect (female, mac); (66) Antennal segments III–VIII, ventral aspect (female, mic); (67) Basantra–mesopresternum (female, mac); (68) Fore tibia &amp; tarsus (female, mac); (69) Fore tibia &amp; tarsus (male, mac); (70) Fore wing; (71) Tube (female, mac)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6404896" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6404896/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="118">Fig. 69</figureCitation>
). From 
<taxonomicName id="E299548D1034FFABDF3BFD68488C2910" authorityName="Okajima &amp; Masumoto" authorityYear="2022" box="[1054,1209,547,573]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Asianthrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="118" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dasycornis">
<emphasis id="17EDF31C1034FFABDF3BFD68488C2910" box="[1054,1209,547,573]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="118">A. dasycornis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="E299548D1034FFABDFECFD68497D2910" authorityName="Okajima &amp; Masumoto" authorityYear="2022" box="[1225,1352,547,573]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Asianthrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="118" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dentipes">
<emphasis id="17EDF31C1034FFABDFECFD68497D2910" box="[1225,1352,547,573]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="118">A. dentipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished easily by the narrowly fused mesopresternum and mesoeusternum (
<figureCitation id="BDA2338B1034FFABDF62FD0C48AA294F" box="[1095,1183,583,610]" captionStart="FIGURES 62–71" captionStartId="16.[151,264,1896,1920]" captionTargetBox="[178,1410,181,1873]" captionTargetId="figure-29@16.[178,1410,181,1873]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURES 62–71. Asianthrips dentipes, sp. n. (62) Head–pelta (female, mac); (63) Head– pelta (female, mic); (64) Antenna, dorsal aspect (female, mic); (65) Antennal segments III–VIII, ventral aspect (female, mac); (66) Antennal segments III–VIII, ventral aspect (female, mic); (67) Basantra–mesopresternum (female, mac); (68) Fore tibia &amp; tarsus (female, mac); (69) Fore tibia &amp; tarsus (male, mac); (70) Fore wing; (71) Tube (female, mac)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6404896" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6404896/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="118">Fig. 67</figureCitation>
). From 
<taxonomicName id="E299548D1034FFABDFD8FD0C4947294C" authorityName="Okajima &amp; Masumoto" authorityYear="2022" box="[1277,1394,583,609]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Asianthrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="118" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="longior">
